name: Security module for php7
description: Suhosin is a great PHP module, but unfortunately, it’s getting old, new ways have been found to compromise PHP applications, and some aren’t working anymore; and it doesn’t play well with the shiny new PHP 7. As a secure web-hosting company, we needed a reliable and future-proof solution to address the flow of new vulnerabilities that are published every day. This is why we developed Snuffleupagus, a new (and open-source!) PHP security module, that provides several features that we needed: passively killing several PHP-specific bug classes, but also implementing virtual-patching at the PHP level, allowing to patch vulnerabilities in a precise, false-positive-free, ultra-low overhead way, without even touching the applications’ code.

description: Monitor and troubleshoot transactions in complex distributed systems
description_good_justification: Monitor and troubleshoot transactions in complex distributed systems.

documentation_basics_justification: Some documentation basics file contents found.
documentation_interface_justification:
Most of the interface that application developers interact with are OpenTracing APIs, which are well documented. Some components, like the Java Client do provide JavaDocs explaining how to consume it (Configuration object) and how to extend it (Sender/MetricsFactory SPIs): https://javadoc.io/doc/io.jaegertracing/jaeger-core

There's currently no supported way to get data in or out of Jaeger directly, although a public Query endpoint will eventually be documented.
https://github.com/jaegertracing/jaeger/issues/456

https://github.com/jaegertracing/jaeger/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md

This does not include specifically "coding style guide", but shows how to run the build, which enforces the style guide.
coding_standards_enforced_justification: Linting is required as part of the continuous integration build.
build_standard_variables_justification: Go flags set via `make` aren't propagated to the final binary.
build_non_recursive_justification: There's only one `make`, using standard Go tools.
build_repeatable_justification: The final binaries are dependent on the exact versions of the dependencies, but they are specified in a file that is committed to the repository (Gopkg.lock). Therefore, it's possible to get the exact versions on subsequent builds. If sources for a dependency at a given tag have changed, the checksum would not match, preventing the build.
installation_standard_variables_justific: There's no installer, the end-user should just place the binary in the most convenient place for the target platform.
regression_tests_added50_justification: As a general rule, every new commit should come with a new test, including fixes for bugs.

name: chrony
description: chrony is a versatile implementation of the Network Time Protocol (NTP). It can synchronise the system clock with NTP servers, reference clocks (e.g. GPS receiver), and manual input using wristwatch and keyboard. It can also operate as an NTPv4 (RFC 5905) server and peer to provide a time service to other computers in the network.
contribution_justification: Patches are submitted to development mailing list. https://chrony.tuxfamily.org/lists.html
contribution_requirements_justification: Detailed documentation on contributing is not provided yet.
license_location_justification: https://git.tuxfamily.org/chrony/chrony.git/tree/COPYING

floss_license_osi_justification: The GPL-2.0 license is approved by the Open Source Initiative (OSI).

version_semver_justification: The project uses major.minor.patch versioning, but incompatible changes may be introduced in minor version updates. They are documented in the NEWS file.
version_tags_justification: Each (pre)release has a signed git tag.
release_notes_vulns_justification: Security issues are listed with CVE IDs in the NEWS file.
report_tracker_justification: Bugs are fixed quickly and the number of unresolved bugs at a time is very small.
report_responses_justification: Most (if not all) bug reports on the mailing list have a response from the maintainer.
enhancement_responses_justification: Most (if not all) enhancement requests on the mailing list have a response from the maintainer.
report_archive_justification:
The mailing lists are archived.
https://chrony.tuxfamily.org/lists.html
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Security issues are reported directly to the maintainer. https://chrony.tuxfamily.org/
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: Typically, there is a response in less than one day.
build_justification: A configure script and makefiles are provided.
test_justification: Two test suites are included. One works on all supported platforms, the other requires special software and works on Linux only.
test_invocation_justification: The test suites are invoked by make check.
tests_documented_added_justification: Detailed documentation on contributing is not provided yet.
warnings_justification: The source code is compiled with the -Wall option.
warnings_strict_justification: The source code is compiled with the -Wall option and source fortification.
crypto_call_justification: The NTP MAC doesn't seem to be supported by the common crypto libraries.
crypto_keylength_justification: The default length of generated symmetric keys is 160 bits. Only keys specified in the key file can be used for authentication, so the user has full control over the minimum key length.
crypto_working_justification: By default, no cryptography is used for security. NTP authentication can be enabled with a symmetric key using a specified cryptographic hash function. The NTP MAC is generally vulnerable to length extension attacks, but the NTP packet format prevents that in all modes supported by chrony (modes 1-5).
crypto_random_justification: Symmetric keys are generated from /dev/urandom or getrandom() if available.
static_analysis_justification: Each release is tested with coverity and clang.
dynamic_analysis_justification: Each release is tested with afl.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: The source code uses assertions. It is tested with valgrind and also ASan, UBSan, MSan.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: By default, no cryptography is used for security. When generating symmetric keys for NTP authentication, SHA-1 is used by default if available. Stronger hashes are supported, but are not used by default for compatibility with widely used NTP implementations.
discussion_justification: https://chrony.tuxfamily.org/lists.html
english_justification: The web site, documentation and mailing lists are all in English.
hardened_site_justification: X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
